<li id="cite_note-25"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25" title="">^</a></b> Mary Pat Fisher (1997) In: Living Religions: An Encyclopedia of the World's Faiths I.B.Tauris&#160;: London <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1860641482" class="internal">ISBN 1860641482</a> - <i>Jainism's major teacher is the Mahavira, a contemporary of the Buddha, and who died approximately 526 BCE. Page 114</i></li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26" title="">^</a></b> Mary Pat Fisher (1997) In: Living Religions: An Encyclopedia of the World's Faiths I.B.Tauris&#160;: London <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1860641482" class="internal">ISBN 1860641482</a> - <i>“The extreme antiquity of Jainism as a non-vedic, indigenous Indian religion is well documented. Ancient Hindu and Buddhist scriptures refer to Jainism as an existing tradition which began long before <a href="/wiki/Mahavira" title="Mahavira">Mahavira</a>.” Page 115</i></li>
